    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="702"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d702">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1386b</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Swedish Minister</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_EWAF1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ekengren</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 26, 1915</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Minister</hi>: I have received your letter
                    delivered by Miss <persName>Hendrickson</persName>, the Chancellor of your
                    Legation, in regard to negotiations between the United States and Great Britain
                    upon the question of neutral rights.<note n="1" xml:id="d702fn1">Not printed;
                        see the letter of the Swedish Minister, July 31, <hi rend="italic"
                        >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_500">p. 500</ref>.</note> As I informed Miss
                        <persName>Hendrickson</persName>, the Department has just received a note
                    from Great Britain in reply to the United States note of March 30, relative to
                    the order in council of March 11.</p>
                <p>I have not, however, had time to read the note which has just been placed on my
                    desk and am, therefore, unable to say at the present moment what the attitude of
                    this Government will be. Of course, this Government will prepare a reply to this
                    British note, and mean-while I shall be glad to discuss with you personally the
                    points of difference between your Government and the British Government, with a
                    view to ascertaining whether it is possible for our two Governments to make more
                    or less uniform representations to the British Government in behalf of the
                    rights of neutrals.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
